ferent  problems.  One,  of  course,  is  awareness  and  the  number  of 
OTA households. 

You  asked  a  few  minutes  ago  about  the  difference  between  Wil-
mington  and  the  United  States  as  a  whole.  Wilmington  has  an 
over-the-air  population  of  only  about  7  percent,  where  the  Nation 
is  at  about  15  percent  based  on  our  consumer  survey.  So  roughly 
double.  So  you  have  to  extrapolate  to  some  extent  the  amount  of 
problems  that  were  faced  in  Wilmington  and  imagine  what  that 
might mean to the United States overall. 

We  have  reported  about  consumer  problems,  even  though  there 
is a considerable range of consumer awareness efforts ongoing from 
the  private  and  the  public  sector.  We  have  also  talked  about  some 

